Imperium and J urisdictio were the two component parts of Officium jus dicentis, i. e. the power of the magistrate (consul, praetor, curule edile) charged with the administration of civil justice.

Of these two elements, J urisdictio denoted the power (perhaps originally vested in the Pontifex) of administering the civil law in the ordinary course of procedure. It consisted chiefly in presiding over the preliminary stages of litigation, and in the period of leg-is actiones was summed up in the utterance of the solemn words, De, Dico, Addico; but in the formulary period it was performed, not by oral utterances, but ΒΥ the delivery of written⁴ documents (verbis conceptis). In genuine litigation it was called jurisdictio contentiosa3 in fictitious litigation, e. g. manumission by vindicta, alienation ΒΥ in jure cessio, it was called jurisdictio voluntaria.
